1 Introduction 
1.1 Project Definition 
Butterflies populations are often utilized as indicator species; from 
monitoring climate change to determining the quality of habitat restoration, 
butterfly numbers are used frequently to help answer scientific questions. However, 
across the nation and world, there is a lack of information on native butterfly 
species, their annual dispersal, and numbers. To fill this gap in information, the 
scientific community has begun relying on citizen scientists - volunteers of various 
backgrounds - to go out into the field and perform butterfly surveys. The 
development of the UBR data recording applications is largely complete. However, to 
further these efforts we would like for the users to be able to analyze their data in an 
online web application with data visualization interfaces [3]. 
1.2 Project Goals 
To complete the suite of mobile applications it is necessary that the UBR5 
team create a solution that collects, exports, and displays surveys made by the 
current user base. Our data may include GPS, weather, butterfly sightings and 
behaviors, and images. The server needs to be able to export user data to any/all 
butterfly organizations. Finally we will provide a way for users to view their data in 
a meaningful way.

2 Design Considerations 
2.1 Design Criteria 
1.Client Usability - Consumer should be able to use and understand final 
product with ease. Even if the final design is complex and includes a lot of 
components, the client and end user should be able to have a simple view and 
understanding of the overall design. 
2.Server-Side Maintainability - Future developers should be able to efficiently 
understand and make changes to our final design. The potential changes 
should be straightforward, code should be well documented and easy to 
understand, and modules should be small and compatible with other 
components. 
3.Product Sustainability - The product should be useable for several years 
without needing to be redesigned. The previous attempt at creating a UBR 
server was not successful in that Parse was deprecated once they completed. 
Each of our design considerations should seek to mitigate dependencies on 
non open source code and unique services. 
4.Partner Ease of Implementation-Partners should be able to interact with our 
system with ease and should be able to view our design in a simple and 
straight-forward manner. 
5.Client Side Ease of Implementation - Future developers or partners should 
not have to implement complex changes in the client-side of the design. It 
must be easy for them to make any required changes, and communicate with 
the server. A system which requires frequent updates and changes should be 
avoided. 
Page 4 of 24 
6.Server Side Ease of Implementation - Implementation of the server should 
not be complex or done from scratch. This may involve some security risks 
because it may not be as secure or efficient as using existing libraries 
combined with more simple and modular design. 
7.Flexibility and Power - The solution should make it easy for future developers 
or partners to interact with our application, handle or make changes to our 
modules/features.  
8.Security - Survey or any other data and user account info should be secure 
and hidden from unauthorized access. Individual users or user-groups should 
be able to access or send data across to other authorized users or user-groups 
securely. 
9.Data Replication and Safety - For guaranteed integrity and security, data 
needs to be backed up safely in multiple locations. This may be accomplished 
automatically by our data storage solution. 
2.2 Design Questions and Decisions 
Over our first semester working on UBR we have analyzed numerous possible 
options and directions for various aspects of our project. The following is what our 
research indicates as the best balance of performance, cost, maintainability, and 
ease of development. 
Presently we have reached out and are awaiting contact from ISUs security 
department as we understand they have concerns about database security, 
particularly in regards to sensitive user data. Given their feedback we may shift 
direction slightly as we develop database access. 
2.2.1 How Should We Provide Visualization on Our Website? 
One goal of this project is to give users a tool they can use to view their data 
in a more understandable and visual format. We have identified two tools we can use 
for this purpose; the Google Maps API[5] and D3.js[6]. 
Component 1: Google Maps API 
Our team has been performing experiments with Google Maps to ascertain 
whether it will function as an efficient mapping tool for our website. Google Maps is 
a well established platform which can be accessed through an open API. Javascript 
can then be used to draw on a map with lines, markers, polygonal shapes, circles, 
location markers, and heatmaps. 
Pros: 
Lightweight and fast. 
An established API with a powerful back end. 
Page 5 of 24 
Cons: 
Somewhat restrictive in terms of display options. 
Component 2: D3.js 
D3.js (D3 for Data-Driven Documents) is a JavaScript library for producing 
dynamic and interactive data visualizations in web browsers. Our team has been 
researching the usage and pros & cons for this technology. We potentially plan on 
using D3.js as a data visualization framework because it is a powerful and flexible 
tool that will allow us to style, manipulate, and make interactive the survey data 
that we will pull in the form of numerous CSV files. 
Pros: 
Strong visualization library with a multitude of examples[6]. 
Cons: 
Applications using D3 for maps are sparse and frequently do not use 
detailed maps. 
Decision 
At present, we will plan to use Google Maps for map displays and D3.js for 
charting and graphing. We may attempt to combine the two[16] to create some truly 
innovative display options, but at time of writing our primary focus is the database 
link that will make UBR a helper to other butterfly research partners. 
2.2.2 What Web Platform Balances Maintainability and Usability? 
One of the goals of this project is to ensure that all of our development work 
enables the teams after us to maintain and modify our code. We need a hosting 
platform which offers us the ability to do this while ensuring that we maintain 
development velocity. Both Platform as a Service (PAAS) and Infrastructure as a 
Service (IAAS) options are available and will be considered. 
PAAS 
Option 1: Googles App-Engine 
A PaaS (platform as a service) cloud computing platform for developing and 
hosting web applications. 
Pros: 
Supports Python, GO, Java, Clojure, JRuby, and PHP.[10] 
Access to the rest of Google services. 
Runs on Googles own cloud infrastructure. 
Automatically scales based on use[10]. 
Prebuilt authentication options[7]. 
Page 6 of 24 
Offers Cloud SQL[13] and NoSQL[14] database options. 
Cons: 
Read-only nature results in tedious and unnecessary code refactoring. 
Apps have to be written specifically with AppEngine in mind[8]. 
Will have to use built in APIs or APIs compatible with App-Engine. 
Option 2: Heroku 
A cloud-based PaaS (platform as a service) provider development platform.  
Pros: 
Offers standard SQL[11]. 
Relatively painless deployment. 
Simpler pricing model[12]. 
Both relational and nonrelational choices in PostgreSQL, MongoDB, Cloudant, and 
REdis. 
Cons: 
Not as large as Google. 
IAAS 
Option 3: Digital Ocean 
Simple IaaS (infrastructure as a service) cloud-hosting provider that gives you 
raw servers to compose as you want to run your app.  
Pros: 
Self-managed virtual servers using DOs interface.  
Very affordable. 
Cons: 
Does not support Windows machines, so no ASP.NET. 
The Digital Ocean management panel lacks features and is somewhat 
buggy. 
There is no way to increase storage space without major downtime. 
There is no way to monitor your bandwidth usage. 
Option 4: Amazon Web Services 
Pros: 
Has highest number of services and options available. 
A service on this platform called EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) allows 
you to increase or decrease storage as needed. 
Page 7 of 24 
Cons: 
Not equipped to handle as many requests as it receives. 
Lacks customer support. 
The number of choices may get confusing to those who are not familiar 
with the different technologies. 
Decision - Google App Engine 
We decided to move forward with Google App Engine as our Platform as a 
Service hosting product. This is in contrast to options such AWS and Digital Ocean 
which are both Infrastructure as a Serviceoptions. The differences are that while 
IaaS will give us more freedom, it does not provide us with anything other than a 
server, while a PaaS host will give us functions such as authentication. [8, 9] Due to 
time constraints, we have determined that primary focus should be on getting the 
application working before the year is over. App engine offers an excellent Platform 
as a Service option which we feel will increase our development velocity. It also 
offers a variety of storage services and APIs highly useful for querying and analysing 
large data sets. We believe it will be a reliable choice as well given its strong track 
record and the fact that other large companies use the service. 
 
2.2.3 What database fits our use case best? 
There are three database models we are considering, SQL and noSQL. Each comes 
with advantages and disadvantages. 
Option 1: SQL 
SQL is an older style that uses tables of key/value pairs to store text data. 
Pros:  
Widely used, numerous developers knowledgeable. 
Industry trusted. 
Has many transactional options. 
Cons: 
Costlier to scale. 
Less flexible. 
Requires significant conversions for use with application logic. 
Less straight-forward security[15]. 
Option 2: NoSQL 
NoSQL is a newer model that stores varied data as documents 
Page 8 of 24 
More flexibility in the storage of data. 
More easily scalable. 
Less conversion between application logic and database. 
Cons: 
Less well known to our developers. 
Some iterations are not as trusted by enterprise. 
Very limited and potentially costly transactional options. 
Option 3: Googles Datastore 
Google offers several database options that are built into or integrate easily 
with the App Engine platform. App Engine offers an SQL and noSQL database as well 
as an option to link outside databases through the Google Compute Engine APIs.  
Firebase is an option that is appealing along with the SQL/noSQL options.  
Pros 
Real-time updates between multiple devices 
Cloud storage, they hold the data for us 
Cross platform API provide database links for mobile and web 
applications 
Cons  
JSON storage format might be more work to query 
Additional cost 
Managed entirely by Google so longevity may be a concern 
Decision - NoSQL 
While SQL does have the largest community, it comes with significant 
drawbacks. The greater security and flexibility of NoSQL make it a better option for 
aiding as-yet-unknown research questions and storing sensitive data. As we have 
decided to use a PAAS design we wanted to use a database option that is already well 
established with Google App Engine. Additionally, Google App Engine offers easy 
Firebase [17] integration, an excellent technology that will greatly aid in our 
bidirectional data flow. We are currently moving forward with the intent to use 
Firebase as our central database. 
2.2.3 What data assurance protocol is best for our database? 
At the heart of a database decision is the data assurance method we want to 
use. 
Option 1: Transactional 
Page 9 of 24 
Transactional databases are the most common among enterprises and ensure 
that any data in the database is consistent with data across all connected users. 
Pros: 
Highly trusted. 
No unused data is stored. 
Cons: 
Limited compatibility with databases. 
No built in backups or history recorded. 
Option 2: Insert-only 
Another option is an insert only approach in which data is not truly 
editable. Any edits made to the data create a copy to be stored as the most current 
version, but the old remains unchanged. 
Pros 
More easily compatible with a variety of databases. 
Automatic backup record. 
Cons 
If backup is unused, space is wasted. 
Option 3: Limit Edit Rights 
A third option is a custom approach that removes concurrent editing 
capabilities. 
Pros: 
Easily implementable. 
We have control over compatibility. 
Cons: 
We would have to restrict edit rights to one user per data set. 
Less scalability. 
Decision- Transactional if allowed by the database 
The database that we are currently looking into (Firebase) has a transactional 
function.  
Page 10 of 24 
2.2.4 How should we provide partner organizations with survey data? 
Users must be able to share their data with partners that they have chosen. We need 
a system wide consistent solution.  
Option 1: Pull model 
We could allow partners to request data via an HTTP request to our server. 
Partners will use our API to request updated data at any time. 
Pros:  
Server-Side Maintainability - Our API is under our control and will not 
be dependent on Partners to maintain. 
Pull cons: 
Partner Ease of Implementation - Partners will need to create a system 
that integrates our API. 
Client Usability - Users data differs from website to website, this may 
cause confusion between the our app and others. 
Decision 
The client has strongly suggested we use the Pull model as described by UBR 
team three[1]. This will allow partners to pull data they have permission to access 
whenever they want it rather than requiring they engage in communication with 
those in charge of the data. We have evaluated their reasoning and come to the 
conclusion that their decision still fits our use case.

3.2 System specifications 
Project requirements specify traits that our application is required to have. 
They will detail the functionalities that our app must provide as well as the 
constraints under which it must be able to operate. We have divided our 
requirements into the web server, web page, and mobile apps. These three main 
sections will detail the functional and non-functional requirements associated with 
them. 
Functional requirements specify the key functionalities and features that our 
application must provide in order to be a viable product. The bulk of the functional 
requirements center around providing a database to support current UBR mobile 
apps, and providing access of our database to other Butterfly databases. [1] 
Non-functional requirements specify the constraints under which our 
features are expected to operate. For our application, weve split these into web 
server requirements and user interface requirements. Most of these requirements 
were discerned by UBR 3. [1] 
 
Page 13 of 24 
3.2.1 Web Server 
Functional Requirements 
The web server must host the web page. 
External agencies are allowed to pull data from the database to aid in 
research.  
The server should prevent data submission from unauthorized sources. 
Non-Functional Requirements 
The system should be maintainable. A new developer should be able to 
understand the system and make modifications to the system very quickly. 
Changes which are likely, such as a change to a partner organizations API 
should correspond to simple and focused changes to our code. 
The system should be able to respond to changes in our partners systems 
with minimal changes and downtime. 
Not Yet Defined Non-Functional Requirements 
The server must accept at least a certain number of requests per day. 
The database should be able to hold at least a given number of sightings. 
The web server and database should remain running and responsive for a 
certain amount of time each month. 
The server and database should respond to all requests within a given number 
of seconds. 
3.2 Web Page 
Functional Requirements 
The web page will provide a visualization tool that allows the user to display 
the data in a variety of ways 
Provide a means to edit the users stored data collection. 
A new Web-Based visualization tool will be created that will allow users to 
analyze their data. 
Non-Functional Requirements 
The user interface should be usable. At least 90% of test subjects given our 
user interface and a task should be able to complete said task without struggle 
or help. 
The user interface should be responsive. The interface should respond to all 
user actions (clicks, taps, button presses, scrolls) within 250ms. This may 
include showing a loading icon or other visual feedback that the action has 
been received and is processing. 
Page 14 of 24 
3.3 Mobile App 
Functional Requirements 
All current UBR functionality will be maintained.  
Updated UBR apps must transmit all survey information to a database over a 
data or wifi connection. If neither connection is available then the data must 
be stored until such a connection can be established.

3.5 Design Analysis 
As stated in section 4.1, our design will follow Clean Architecture[4]. In accordance 
with this, each object with connections to an external system (i.e. Web Server 
contacting the DB) will do so through a translator module. These modules will have 
predefined functions which in turn build the communication protocols. By building 
the project this way we can swap any given translator out for another with the exact 
same functions which will allow us and/or future developers to switch between 
technologies should the need arise. 
4 Testing/Development 
The goal for UBR5 is to be developed using Agile Scrum. A demo-able product every 
sprint, layering itself into the current product. Every new feature will adhere to the 
following guidelines. 
1.Testing will be done for each commit, covering the code written or updated. 
Page 19 of 24 
2.When a bug is found, a bug fix request will be submitted via github covering 
the broken code. 
3.Tests will not be modified unless they are found to be incorrect incorrect or 
become incorrect due to a change in the use cases. 
4.Pull requests will not be accepted unless all tests are passing on a given 
members branch. 
5 Conclusions 
Our Design document remains largely unfinished due to time constraints and 
will be updated throughout the week to provide greater detail of what we have been 
working toward over this semester. What we have provided hopefully conveys a solid 
framework for the design document we hope to achieve by the next iteration.
